04461nam a22005415i 9780822385998DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20042004ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223859987 a10.1515/97808223859982doi  a(DE-B1597)551865  a(OCoLC)1055303746  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aML3524b.F69 2004 7aMUS0100002bisacsh1 aFox, Aaron A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aReal Country :bMusic and Language in Working-Class Culture /cAaron A. Fox. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2004] 4cÂ©2004  a1 online resource (382 p.) :b40 b&w photos, 1 figure  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tA Note on Transcription Conventions -- tPrelude: ''Turns'' -- t1 Voicing Working-Class Culture -- t2 Knowing Lockhart: Two Perspectives -- t3 ''Out the Country'': Space, Time, and Stereotype -- t4 ''The Fool in the Mirror'': Self, Person, and Subjectivity -- t5 ''Feeling'' and ''Relating'': Speech, Song, Story, and Emotion -- tInterlude: Photo Essay -- t6 ''Bring Me Up in a Beer Joint'': The Poetics of Speech and Song -- t7 ''The Women Take Care of That'': Engendering Working-Class Culture -- t8 The Art of Singing: Speech and Song in Performance -- t9 ''I Hang My Head and Cry'': The Character of the Voice -- tCoda: Indigenous to Modernity -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tAppendix -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Lockhart, Texas, a rural working-class town just south of Austin, country music is a way of life. Conversation slips easily into song, and the songs are full of conversation. Anthropologist and musician Aaron A. Fox spent years in Lockhart making research notes, music, and friends. In Real Country, he provides an intimate, in-depth ethnography of the community and its music. Showing that country music is deeply embedded in the textures of working-class life, Fox argues that it is the cultural and intellectual property of working-class people and not only of the Nashville-based music industry or the stars whose lives figure so prominently in popular and scholarly writing about the genre.Fox spent hundreds of hours observing, recording, and participating in talk and music-making in homes, beer joints, and garage jam sessions. He renders the everyday life of Lockhart's working-class community in detail, right down to the ice cold beer, the battered guitars, and the technical skills of such local musical legends as Randy Meyer and Larry "Hoppy" Hopkins. Throughout, Fox focuses on the human voice. His analyses of conversations, interviews, songs, and vocal techniques show how feeling and experience are expressed, and how local understandings of place, memory, musical aesthetics, working-class social history, race, and gender are shared. In Real Country, working-class Texans re-imagine their past and give voice to the struggles and satisfactions of their lives in the present through music.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aCountry musiczTexaszLockhartxHistory and criticism. 0aMusic and language. 0aWorking classzTexaszLockhartvSongs and musicxHistory and criticism. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Country & Bluegrass.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822385998zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822385998423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822385998.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles